Part I - Ford GoBike Trip Data Exploration¶

by George Kariuki¶

Introduction¶

Ford created FORD GO BIKES in a bid to provide sustainable means of transport apart from vehicles. The data used below provides insights into ages, stations, user groups and gender.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 183,412 records/ rows and 16 features including - duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id,start_station_name, start_station_latitude,start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name,end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type,member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip.

9 features are numeric, 2 features are datetime objects, 1 boolean based feature and 4 objects based features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest in the dataset is the duration of each trip.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I would like to investigate the duration of each trip based on user type, gender, and start station and end station, and their ages.

base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
def plot_hist(features, bins_size=100, data=ford_copy, figsize=[18,6]):
    """This function plots histograms"""
    rows = 1
    col = len(features)
    count = 1
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for i in features:
        plt.subplot(rows, col, features.index(i)+1)
        plt.hist(data=data, x=i,
                bins=np.arange(data[i].min(), data[i].max()+bins_size, bins_size),
                color = base_color
                );
        plt.xlabel(i)
        plt.ylabel('Count')
        plt.title('Distribution of '+ i);

def plot_bar(features, data=ford_copy, figsize=[20,6]):
    """This function plots bar charts"""
    rows = 1
    col = len(features)
    count = 1
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for i in features:
        plt.subplot(rows, col, features.index(i)+1)
        height = data[i].value_counts()
        x = data[i].value_counts().index
        plt.bar(data=data, x=x, height=height, color=base_color);   
        plt.xlabel(i)
        plt.ylabel('Count') 
        plt.title('Distribution of '+i);
        
def plot_box(col, data=ford_copy, figsize=[8,6]):
    """This function plots box plots"""
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=col, color=base_color);    
    plt.title('Distribution of '+col);

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The Distribution of the Duration feature introduced us to a highly skewed curve - after setting a small bin size and magnifying the graph on a small area. The histogram proved that the Duration was a unimodal curve. However, a log scale provided a more normal distribution than the previous, but it still had a longer right tail than a left tail.

The data revealed that most trips revolve around 500 to 1000 seconds per trip - this roughly translates to 10 to 20 minutes. These are relatively short rides meaning the distance is equally as short.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

AGE: The boxplot revealed that there were outliers in the data dating all the way to 1880. I created an AGE feature revealing that the data is skewed to the right. The data reveals that majority of the users are between 20 and 40.

GENDER: The bar plot reveals that most of the users were male users more than the female and the 'other' gender in the data.

USER TYPE: The bar plot shows that there were more subscribers than casual customers.

BIKE SHARE FOR ALL TRIP: More people did not share their trip data.

STATIONS: The two histograms revealed show a high level of similarity between the start station and the end station. This reveals that there are some stations that receive more users than the others.

def plot_scatter(features, y='duration_sec', log=True, alpha=0.1, data=ford_copy, figsize=[18,6]):
    "Plots a scatter plot"
    rows = 1
    col = len(features)
    count = 1
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for i in features:
        plt.subplot(rows, col, features.index(i)+1)
        plt.scatter(data=data, x=i, y=y, color=base_color, alpha=alpha);
        if log:
            plt.yscale('log')
            plt.yticks([100, 1000, 10000, 100000],['100', '1000', '10000', '100000'])
        plt.ylabel(y)    
        plt.title('Distribution of '+i+' against '+y)
        plt.xlabel(i);

def plot_heatmap(features, y, bins_x=20, cmin=100, ylim=None, bins_y=20, log=False, data=ford_copy, figsize=[18,6]):
    "Plots a scatter plot"
    rows = 1
    col = len(features)
    count = 1
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for i in features:
        plt.subplot(rows, col, features.index(i)+1)
        binx = np.arange(data[i].min(), ford_copy[i].max()+bins_x, bins_x)
        biny = np.arange(data[y].min(), ford_copy[y].max()+bins_y, bins_y)
        plt.hist2d(data=ford_copy, x=i, y=y, bins=[binx, biny], cmin=cmin, cmap='viridis_r')
        plt.colorbar()
        if log and y=='duration_sec':
            plt.yscale('log')
            plt.yticks([100, 300, 1000, 3000, 10000, 30000, 100000],['100', '300', '1000', '3000', '10000', '30000', '100000'])
            plt.ylim(100, 10000)
        if y=='age':
            plt.ylim(ylim)
        plt.ylabel(y)    
        plt.title('Heat map of '+i+' against '+y)
        plt.xlabel(i);

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Age and Duration:

These two features had a slightly negative correlation to each other. Younger participants rode the bikes more than the older users. With the alpha value in the scatter plot set to as low as 1/10, there was a gradual decline observed as the age increased.

The heatmap gave a clearer indication that the most active users were between the age of 20-40 going for bike rides. This group was closely followed by the 40-60 group. Lastly the 60-80 group.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Stations and Duration:

The scatter plots of start_station_id and end_station_id revealed the same thing. Some stations in the data received higher logs of the duration in comparison to others. The heatmaps revealed that on average the lower id stations were logging a lot more rides than others. This could either be attributed to more bikes at the station, a high population in the area, or a culture of bike riding around the areas in those stations. Could age, gender and user type be attributed to this too?

Age and Stations:

The Heatmap reveals that the most populous age group is the 20-40 group, mostly found in the first few stations. Other age groups are not as active across stations.

Age and User Type:

The box plot revealed that the Subscriber and Customer ages were roughly the same with a median of 35 across both categories.

Age and Genders:

The median age of the male riders is about 35 while the female riders is slightly lower than that of the male riders. The riders who identified as others had a median age higher than that of the male riders.

def sns_scatter(features, x, y='duration_sec', log=True, data=ford_copy, figsize=[18,6]):
    "Plots a scatter plot"
    rows = 1
    col = len(features)
    count = 1
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for i in features:
        plt.subplot(rows, col, features.index(i)+1)
        sns.scatterplot(data=data, x=x, y=y, hue=i);
        if log:
            plt.yscale('log')
            plt.yticks([100, 1000, 10000, 100000],['100', '1000', '10000', '100000'])
        plt.ylabel('Duration(sec)')  
        plt.title('Distribution of '+x+' against '+y+' with a hue of '+i);

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Age and Duration - User Type

Both the scatter plots revealed that there was an almost normal curve. Both curves were skewed to the right. The peak for the susbcribers was much higher than that of the customers.

Age and Duration - Gender

There were more males in the lower regions of the 20 - 40 age group than there were in the female category. It was also interesting to note that the 60 - 80 category also showed more men in there than women in the same category. The gender other was most populous between the 25-50 range, but not as compared to the male and female categories.

Stations and Duration - Gender

These curves provided the same result. The distribution of males was almost identical to that of the females and others.

Age and Duration - User Type

These curves provided the same result. The distribution of Subscribers was denser than that of the customers but both graphs visually had the same curve.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Age and Duration - User Type

It was interesting to see that the riders who took the longer rides were customers than subscribers. Perhaps these riders were not from the city and wanted to spend longer periods with the bikes.

Age and Duration - Gender

The scatter plot reveals that both males and females took longer rides despite what we might naturally presume that females would take shorter durations. All genders are all in the pool of shorter rides making the graph densely populated in the lower regions.

Conclusions¶

In summary I have found out

  • The data did not have a column for ages, owing of course to the fact that every year the ages will change. I added the column to allow visualisations with ages against the other features.
  • Duration is closely related to the age of the riders - It was suprising to see that 80 year olds were part of the riding statistics despite their ages.
  • Start Stations and End Stations receive the same level of traffic and no start station is partly more used than the other. Visually riders will start and end their rides at the same stations.
  • Although Subscribers are more that the Customers, Customers seem to take longer periods per trip than subscribers.
  • Although younger people are more than the older generation, they are not taking longer rides as would be expected.
